## [FAIL] [AMBIGUITY] — Two different empty-value semantics for stored mail-texts
**Where:** Spec line 399 "Admin saved leeren `intro` → `intro = ""` → bei Render fällt Defaults aus dict zurück (mergeMailWithDefaults)" vs M1 implementation `submission-form-fields.ts:100` which TRIMS whitespace before fallback
**Gap:** M1's `mergeWithDefaults` says: `const trimmed = typeof v === "string" ? v.trim() : ""; (merged as Record<string, string>)[k] = trimmed ? (v as string) : defaults[k];` — i.e. whitespace-only strings ALSO fall back to defaults. The M2 spec says only "leeren `intro`" (empty string). Generator may write a stricter or looser version. If looser (`v ?? defaults[k]`), `"   "` survives as a whitespace-only mail-subject. If stricter (`!v.trim() ? defaults[k] : v.trim()`), the saved value is implicitly trimmed in the editor → user types "Hallo " (trailing space, intentional separator) → DB stores "Hallo".
**Implementation hazard:** Drift from M1 semantics. Tests for the new editor pass with either implementation but the user-experience is inconsistent across the two editors (Form-Texte trims to fallback, Mail-Texte does not — or vice versa). Codex will catch this in PR-R1 as "M1/M2 inconsistency".
**Suggested fix:** Spec must explicitly state: "`mergeMailWithDefaults` follows M1 trim-aware semantics: a stored value that is empty OR whitespace-only falls back to the default. Saved values are NOT trimmed at save-time — admin's exact characters round-trip preserved." Also DK-7 must include test case `interpolate("Hallo {{vorname}}", {vorname: "  "})` and `mergeMailWithDefaults({...intro:"   "}, defaults)` returns the dict default.

